    {
      "id": "T18",
      "desc": "translate Japanese",
      "called_tool": null,
      "called_tools": [],
      "expected_tool": "translate",
      "expected_tools": null,
      "tool_correct": false,
      "params_correct": false,
      "params_detail": {},
      "score": 0.0,
      "raw_content": "In Japanese, there are several ways to say \"goodbye,\" depending on the level of formality and the situation:\n\n1. **\u3055\u3088\u3046\u306a\u3089 (sayounara)** - The most common and formal way to say goodbye. Used in professional settings or with people you don't know well.\n\n2. **\u3058\u3083\u3042 (jaa)** - A casual \"see ya\" or \"okay then.\" Very commonly used in everyday conversation.\n\n3. **\u307e\u305f\u306d (mata ne)** - Means \"see you again.\" Friendly and casual, often used when you expect to see the person again.\n\n4. **\u3058\u3083\u3042\u306d (jaa ne)** - A casual \"see ya later.\" Similar to \"jaa\" but with a slightly softer tone.\n\n5. **\u3070\u3044\u3070\u3044 (bai bai)** - Very casual, like \"bye-bye.\" Used with close friends or children.\n\n6. **\u304a\u5143\u6c17\u3067 (ogenki de)** - A polite way to say \"take care\" or \"stay healthy,\" often used when parting ways.\n\nThe most versatile and commonly used in everyday situations is **\u3055\u3088\u3046\u306a\u3089 (sayounara)** for formal situations and **\u3058\u3083\u3042 (jaa)** or **\u307e\u305f\u306d (mata ne)** for casual situations.",
